LLM (large language model)
> NLP, GenAI, AgenticAI


bulk text (huge) ---> [[machine]]
> machine / electronic device trained on huge amount of text / data is called LLM
> coz of training machine able to 
    > read, write, summarize, translate, answer (questions), write code
    > understand context, intent, meaning, tone of content
    > LLM also has capability of prediction

Ex: supply LLM a demo.pdf (100 pages) and ask summarize to 10 pages or translate, it will be able to do it

Ex of models using LLM are ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini

> LLMs are based on Transformers architecture


Transformers architecture:

input data --> Tokenization --> Embedding layer --> transformer blocks

> --> transformer blocks -> self attention -> self attention mechanism -> Output layer

> --> transformer blocks -> feed forward -> feed forward network -> Output layer

--> Output layer --> training & loss optimization

Tokenization:
> convert input data into tokens is called Tokenization

1- Word Tokenization:
> sentences broken to words
Ex; input --> what is AI (Machine cannot understand this)
> convert this to tokens
> Ex: ["what", "is", "AI"]
> this is example of Word Tokenization
> Drawbacks:
    > it becomes huge vocabulary
    > reuse doesn't exist
    > unable to handle new words

2- Character Tokenization:
Ex: I love LLM
["I", "L", "o", "v", "e", "L", "L", "M"]
> Drawbacks:
    > it becomes huge vocabulary
    > slow due to huge vocabulary

3 - Subword Tokenization or Byte Pair Encoding:
> used in GPT models
> Ex: unhappiness
["un", "happi", "ness"]
> Machine knows these tokens coz of training using huge amount of data
> advantages:
    > able to handle unknown words
    > smaller vocabulary
    > efficient compared to word & Character Tokenization

> Ex: in 100 pages pdf lets say words that exist is "low", "lower", "lowest"
> number of times that are repeated in input pdf is ["low"]
> then next ["er"] & ["est"]
> So in subword Tokenization it becomes ["low", "er", "est"]
> this is also called as Byte Pair Encoding (BPE)

> Predefined library in Python is "transformers"

> Example of another IDE like VS Code is "google colab"


input
> Tokenization
> Embeddings (converting token ids to number vectors)
> Positional Encoding (to overcome meaning in sentence like Dog bites man / man bites dog)
> Self attention (find the relationship)
> multi head attention (grammer, emotion, context, action)
> Feed forward layers
> output (softmax)

Vector DB:
> Shows good performance for storing vectors
> It is a NoSQL DB

RAG protocol:
> Restricting given data to train LLM within network is called RAG protocol
> providing external data is called protocol

langchain:
> LLM framework
> define llm flow

pypdf:
> read pdf file

sentence-transformers
> used to create Embedding

chromadb:
> used to connect to vector DB

openai:
> used to generate AI output

python-multipart:
> used to upload the pdf files

Chunking:
> LLM able to handle 500 characters or less at a time
> dividing large text into packets (threshold number of characters) that LLM can process is called chunking
